<DOC><DOCNO> AP900613-0221 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-90 1349EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv15   06-13 0555</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 15,0577</SECOND><NOTE>$adv15</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Friday AMs, June 15</NOTE><DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The world's Christian population grew byabout 326 million during the past decade to an estimated 1.75billion, an expert on religious statistics says.   The Rev. David Barrett, an Anglican priest, editor of the WorldChristian Encyclopedia and now a consultant to the Southern BaptistForeign Mission Board, cited the figures in the InternationalBulletin of Missionary Research.   The new total amounts to about 33 percent of the world's 5.3billion people. It includes 963 million Roman Catholics, 324million Protestants, 180 million Eastern Orthodox and 54 millionAnglicans, the ecumenical fortnightly Christianity Today reports.   An additional 232 million Christians were not included in thosegroupings.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Cross Currents, an influentialquarterly journal that for 50 years has explored the implicationsof religion for modern life, is merging with another quarterly,Religion andamp; Intellectual Life.   Cross Current's founding editor, Joseph Cunneen, and associateWilliam Birmingham will be co-editors with Sister Nancy Malone ofthe Association for Religion and Intellectual Life.   The name of the new combined publication is Cross Currents:Religion andamp; Intellectual Life.</TEXT><DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Many church leaders were involved in recentprotest demonstrations against the death penalty in Florida,Georgia and North Carolina.   In demonstrations in Raleigh and Atlanta, a statement byEpiscopal Presiding Bishop Edmond L. Browning was read, calling thedeath penalty ``an affront to God'' because all people are made inGod's image.   ``The taking of human life diminishes us as a people,'' because``we end up committing the very act we found so repugnant in thefirst place,'' he said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The American Jewish Committe has endorsed inprinciple electoral and constitutional reforms for the state ofIsrael, but says only Israeli citizens can determine whether and inwhat form such steps occur.   AJC President Sholom D. Commay said: ``We believe that electoralreforms should be enacted, and protections of human rights shouldbe more explicitly and firmly codified into the legal structure ofIsrael, so that the nation may better cope with its own unique andoften perilous problems.''</TEXT><DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Back from conferring with church leaders in thePhilippines, the president of the Lutheran Church-Missouri Synodsaid basic elements remain of links to the Lutheran Church in thePhilippines.   The board of directors of the Philippine church voted in Marchto sever its relationship with the 2.6 million-member denominationbased in Missouri.   The Rev. Ralph A. Bohlmann, president of the Missouri Synod,said the talks convinced him the ``basic component of ourfellowship is intact. ... Given time to heal, this relationship canbe salvaged and restored.''   However, he said, only the Philippine church can resolveproblems at the root of the interchurch difficulty.</TEXT><DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Christian monitoring organization saysnetwork television reduced the amount of sex, violence, profanityand anti-Christian stereotyping last year by 32 percent.   The Rev. Billy Melvin, chairman of Christian Leaders forResponsible Television, says some companies apparently wereresponding to the organization's activity in the shows they sponsor.   The group is a coalition of about 1,600 Christian leaders fromnearly every denomination, including top leaders of about 70denominations.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Friday AMs, June 15</NOTE></DOC>